abstract: The Missouri River has a world-wide reputation for muddiness. Some power may, by a miraculous means, wash the River Rhine, but any such attempt upon the dirty-brown flood of the Missouri will be sure to result in ignominious failure. Has ever poet ventured to sing the praises of this turbid stream? His river god must be yellow-haired with a vengeance, and his complexion more saffron-like than a Chinaman afflicted with jaundice.

abstract: WASHINGTON, July 7--1 A. M.?The central area of lowest pressure has moved eastward from Iowa since Wednesday night and is now on Lake Ontario. abstract: The deepening of the Illinois and Michigan Canal at Summit, was completed yesterday, and the dam at Bridgeport cut away. The waters of Lake Michigan and the Chicago River are now flowing in the direction of the Illinois River to the Mississippi. The work of deepening the Canal has been in progress about five years, and has cost the city of Chicago over $3,000,000.

abstract: A terrific tornado, accompanied by thunder, lightning and heavy rain, passed over Vineland, N.J., on Sunday evening. Roofs of houses, trees and fences were destroyed. abstract: DENVER, Col., July 16.--An immense amount of building is in progress here. Not less than thirty first-class iron-front store-rooms are now under contract, beside a very large number of private residences. The weather for the past week has been extremely hot. abstract: A Court-martial has been called to try Alderman JAMES A. GEAYER, of Hoboken, for insubordination on the 12th inst. Mr. GEAYER is a member of Major HANT'S battalion, which was on duty upon that day. The Alderman, during the afternoon, asked to be excused from further duty, in order to go to New-York. This was refused, and he forthwith doffed his uniform and went without the desired permission. The trial will take place next week.
